go-to: zhili_congress_menu

= Party Congress

{!<svg id="reichstag" style="width: 500px; height: 250px;"> </svg>!}

With the news on the conflict still hot and coming in and the Brockdorff cabinet still busy discussing course of action, the SPD chooses to host their party conference in the town of [BLANK] for logistical purposes. As the delegates make their way in from all over the country, the atmosphere is quite tense and uncertain, in other part due to how unusual it is. 

Since the March Reforms, the SPD has not been known for taking strong action on foreign affairs and we have remained mostly inactive since forcing Luderndoff's hand into peace. However, Stresemann's proposal to intervene in 1924 led to outrage from the war weary German population, causing his and Reichskanzler Arthur von Posadowsky-Wehner's entire cabinet to fall. Meanwhile the Chinese Intervention has been acquiring grumblings among the less warhawky sides of society. Many in our party left, previously aligned with the USPD, believe it is our duty to take strong action to stop Imperialism.

Even so, the conference was met with significant doubt from many of the delegates who are more distrustful of the party leadership across the entire SPD aisle, and thus come with a degree of opposition to any decisions that can be made here.

At , Party Chairman Hermann Muller declares the opening, 

